This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for deterministic parallel work.

## Core concept

Parallel compilation is correct only when completion order cannot change semantic identities, diagnostics or output.

## Beanstalk boundary

- Graph dependencies determine which modules may run together.
- Module identities and source order are canonical before workers run.
- File deltas merge in original source order.
- Module deltas merge in canonical module order.
- Diagnostics never merge in worker-completion order.
- Provider-backed discovery remains serial until it has deterministic deltas.
- Generated-function requests use one deterministic fixed-point worklist.
- Locks around mutable AST state do not create a sound parallel ownership model.

## Rewrite focus

Explain dependency waves, deterministic reduction, interning and remapping, reproducible diagnostics and why parallelism requires data ownership rather than lock wrapping.

Canonical details live in both architecture authorities.
